The debt to income ratio and income are negatively correlated, which is expected as debts don't typically increase in the same proportion as income. FICO score and income are positively correlated, which is also not surprising since individuals with higher income are typically more financially literate.

    accuracy = cross_val_score(estimator = DecisionTreeClassifier(ccp_alpha=alpha), X = X_train, y = y_train, cv = 5 , scoring="accuracy" )

Accuracy of 65% is better, and F1 score seems to have increased. Precision is the same. The main fishy thing here is that recall is now 100% meaing that the model is capturing true postives perfectly - it seems like we may be overfitting and looking at the confusion matrix it seems that this model is simply putting all observations as loan_status=1 (in fact, our target variable has an almost perfect 65/35 split so with accuracy of 65% we're pretty confident that this is what's happening).

Additionally, the statistics for loan_status=0 are all 0 now, which doesn't seem normal but we aren't sure what's going on.

In [46]:
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(25,20))
DT_plot = tree.plot_tree(dtree, feature_names=X_train.columns, filled=True, max_depth=4, class_names=True)
# left branch True

The best split in this tree (lowest gini number) is at fico <= 682.5.

Say there's an invidual with an income of 100 and a FICO score of 730. At the first split, income is greater than 89.25 so we go down the right side (left=true). At this split, our FICO score is greater than 682.5, so we go down the right side again. This leaves us at the leaf node to the furthest right, which gives us loan_status=1.

There are 4 terminal nodes and this is because we set the minimum samples leaf at 50 and the depth at 4.

No we are not satisified, these gini numbers are pretty high. The closer we get to .5, the closer we are to doing no better than random.
